#!/usr/bin/env python3
"""led -- read from and write to this project's decision ledger.

usage: led <kind> <statement...> [flags]        write an entry (decision, finding, assumption, ...)
       led --recent [N] | led current [N] | led show <id>
       led question-status | review-gap | stamp-distinctness | standing
       led register-principal <name> <class> [--purpose "<why>"]
       led obligate <scope> <assigned-by> <obliged-actor>
       led obligate revoke <scope> --reason "<text>"
       led review <entry-id> <verdict> <independence> <statement...>
       led work open|claim|depends|close|list|violations|asof|review-gap|startable|
           resolve-violation|supersede-cascade ...   (see `led work <sub-verb>` with no args)
       led artifact put <path> | get <hash> | stat <hash>
       led principal <sub-verb> ...                  (see `led principal` with no args)
       led decomposition-review-status | led briefing
       led --json <ledger|review|registration|obligation> <file|->

Run any subcommand with no arguments, or a malformed one, for its own one-line usage. Every
entry is attributed to the actual connection identity, never a name you type; `led --recent`
and `led show <id>` read entries back.

This CLI talks HTTP to this project's boundary service rather than psql directly (the served
rebase, design/FABLE-BOUNDARY-MULTIPLEX-AND-CLI-REBASE-SPEC.md §5, ratified ledger row 1631).
Full coverage detail, transport/exit-code conventions, and every disclosed behavior difference
from the retired direct-psql tool (`./legacy/led`, now a one-line teaching-refusal stub) are
kept verbatim, not deleted (ADR-0020), in
design/LED-BOUNDARY-REBASE-COVERAGE.md -- nobody needs to read that file to use this tool.

TRANSPORT: every read is a GET against `/rows/*`/`/views/*`/`/standing/principals` (paginated,
walked to completion client-side, spec's own "no server-side filter grammar" discipline); every
write is a POST against `/write/<surface>`, the kernel's own `write_verdict` passed through
byte-verbatim (spec §5: "same typed verdicts"). Exit codes follow `boundary_cli_client.py`'s own
convention (module docstring there): 0 kernel-accepted, 1 kernel-refused (byte-identical to the
legacy tool's own exit for this case), 3 boundary-refused, 4 boundary-unreachable/client error.

Lazy imports banned (CLAUDE.md, 2026-07-02): every import is top-of-file."""
